<p>My first peer-reviewed paper, titled <a href="https://doi.org/10.1103/PhysRevAccelBeams.24.044201"><em>Computation of the matched envelope of the Danilov distribution</em></a> {% cite Hoover2021 %}, was published in Physical Review Accelerators and Beams (PRAB) at the end of April. I thought I would summarize the results of the paper and share the code I used to generate those results. I'll try to focus on the main results to avoid re-writing the entire paper here.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h2 id="Self-consistent-beams">Self-consistent beams<a class="anchor-link" href="#Self-consistent-beams"> </a></h2>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>This work falls under the topic of <em>self-consistent beams</em>; I'll start by defining this term. The posts I've written on <a href="https://austin-hoover.github.io/blog/physics/accelerators/simulation/space%20charge/2021/02/22/PIC.html">space charge</a> as well as <a href="https://austin-hoover.github.io/blog/physics/accelerators/coupling/2021/01/25/coupled_parametric_oscillators.html">coupled motion</a> may be helpful.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h3 id="Definition-and-attractive-properties">Definition and attractive properties<a class="anchor-link" href="#Definition-and-attractive-properties"> </a></h3>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>We define a beam to be self-consistent if it satisfies the following conditions:</p>
<ol>
<li>It gives rise to linear space charge forces.</li>
<li>The above point remains true as long as all external forces are linear.</li>
</ol>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>Let's discuss the meaning and relevance of these conditions. <em>Space charge forces</em> are the forces which arise between charged particles in a beam. <em>Linear</em> refers to the dependence of the magnitude of this force on the position in the beam. For example, consider the following two distributions of charged particles and the radial electric field they produce.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>The distribution on the left produces an electric field which is proportional to the radius within a sharp circular boundary, i.e., it gives rise to linear space charge forces. The distribution on the right, on the other hand, produces an electric field which depends nonlinearly on the radius, i.e., it gives rise the nonlinear space charge forces.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>Nonlinear forces bring with them several negative effects. One of these effects is emittance growth. Emittance is a measure of the area occupied by the beam in phase space, so it measures both the variance in position and the variance in momentum among the beam particles. It's usually important to keep the emittance as small as possible; for example, a smaller emittance means a larger luminosity in a collider. The key point here is that the emittance is invariant as long as all forces are linear. [Need to expand on this section. Maybe define emittance along with a figure, and maybe show a simulation example in which the emittance grows, along with the initial and final x-x' distributions].</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>Another effect of space charge in circular machines is called <em>tune shift</em>. Recall that the single-particle tune is the number of oscillations a particle undergoes in phase space during one trip around the accelerator. Space charge decreases the tune of every particle (a helpful analogy is a mass on a spring; weakening the spring will decrease the oscillation frequency of the mass). This is annoying because the tunes need to be precisely chosen to avoid <a href="https://austin-hoover.github.io/blog/physics/accelerators/nonlinear%20systems/resonances/2021/03/28/nonlinear_resonances.html">resonances</a> driven by nonlinear magnetic fields. If the horizontal and vertical tunes are $\nu_x$ and $\nu_y$, a common strategy is to avoid any resonance lines up to a certain order defined by $M_x \nu_x + M_y \nu_y = N$, where $M_x$, $M_y$, and $N$ are integers and $|M_x| + |M_y|$ is the order of the resonance; if a particle lies on one of these lines in tune space, it is likely that it will be driven to large amplitudes and eventually lost. No problem, we'll just make sure the tune doesn't cross any resonance lines as it shifts. But there is another effect called the <em>tune spread</em> which complicates things. The complication is that nonlinear forces cause the tune shift to depend on particle position; the beam spreads out in tune space as a consequence since the tune of each particle is reduced by a different amount. This increases the chance that some particles will hit resonance lines. [Show the classic photo from SNS, or run your own simulation].</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>The final downside of nonlinear space charge forces is a loss of analytic tractability. Accelerator physics deals with particles moving in time-dependent fields, and an analytic solution exists when these forces are linear. Space charge introduces the self-consistency problem: each particle moves due to the collective beam electric field, which modifies the field, which moves the particles, etc. In general, there is no analytic solution to this problem and we must turn to expensive computer simulations.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>At this point it's (hopefully) clear that a beam with linear space charge forces would alleviate several problems. In fact, we already showed an example of such a beam. Say we took this beam and transported through an accelerator; would its uniform density be maintained? To answer this question, we would need to specify the initial distribution of the particle <em>velocities</em> in addition to the initial positions; it turns out that there are only a few special cases for which the answer is yes. We call these cases self-consistent beams.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h3 id="KV-distribution">KV distribution<a class="anchor-link" href="#KV-distribution"> </a></h3>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>The first self-consistent beam, now known as the KV distribution, was derived by a pair of Russian scientists in 1959. Particles in the KV distribution uniformly populate the boundary of an ellipsoid (or sphere in certain coordinates) in 4D phase space ($x$, $x'$, $y$, $y'$). Interestingly, any 2D projection leads to a uniform density ellipse. To generate this distribution, we can first create a 4D Gaussian, then normalize all vectors to unit length so that they populate a spherical shell.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
    {% raw %}
    
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<details class="description">
      <summary class="btn btn-sm" data-open="Hide Code" data-close="Show Code"></summary>
        <p><div class="input">

<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">X</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">random</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">normal</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">size</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">100000</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">4</span><span class="p">))</span>
<span class="n">X</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">apply_along_axis</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="k">lambda</span> <span class="n">x</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="n">x</span> <span class="o">/</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">linalg</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">norm</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">x</span><span class="p">),</span> <span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">X</span><span class="p">)</span>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>The really cool thing about the KV distribution is that we can predict the evolution of the elliptical boundary containing the particles in the $x$-$y$ plane; we call this the beam <em>envelope</em>. Instead of running an expensive PIC simulation, we can just integrate a system of differential equations. Details about these equations can be found [here].</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
    {% raw %}
    
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="kn">from</span> <span class="nn">scipy.integrate</span> <span class="kn">import</span> <span class="n">odeint</span>
<span class="kn">import</span> <span class="nn">pandas</span> <span class="k">as</span> <span class="nn">pd</span>

<span class="k">class</span> <span class="nc">EnvelopeSolver</span><span class="p">:</span>
    <span class="k">def</span> <span class="fm">__init__</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="bp">self</span><span class="p">):</span>
        <span class="bp">self</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">positions</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="bp">self</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">moments</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="kc">None</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="kc">None</span>
        
    <span class="k">def</span> <span class="nf">vec2mat</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="bp">self</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">moments</span><span class="p">):</span>
        <span class="p">(</span><span class="n">sig11</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">sig12</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">sig13</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">sig14</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">sig22</span><span class="p">,</span> 
         <span class="n">sig23</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">sig24</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">sig33</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">sig34</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">sig44</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">moments</span>
        <span class="k">return</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">array</span><span class="p">([[</span><span class="n">sig11</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">sig12</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">sig13</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">sig14</span><span class="p">],</span> 
                         <span class="p">[</span><span class="n">sig12</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">sig22</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">sig23</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">sig24</span><span class="p">],</span>
                         <span class="p">[</span><span class="n">sig13</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">sig23</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">sig33</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">sig34</span><span class="p">],</span>
                         <span class="p">[</span><span class="n">sig14</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">sig24</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">sig34</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">sig44</span><span class="p">]])</span>
    
    <span class="k">def</span> <span class="nf">mat2vec</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="bp">self</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">Sigma</span><span class="p">):</span>
        <span class="k">return</span> <span class="n">Sigma</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">triu_indices</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">4</span><span class="p">)]</span>
    
    <span class="k">def</span> <span class="nf">get_shape_factors</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="bp">self</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">Sigma</span><span class="p">):</span>
        <span class="n">sig11</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">sig33</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">sig13</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">Sigma</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">],</span> <span class="n">Sigma</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">2</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">2</span><span class="p">],</span> <span class="n">Sigma</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">2</span><span class="p">]</span>
        <span class="n">S0</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">sqrt</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">sig11</span> <span class="o">*</span> <span class="n">sig33</span> <span class="o">-</span> <span class="n">sig13</span><span class="o">**</span><span class="mi">2</span><span class="p">)</span>
        <span class="n">Sx</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">Sy</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">sig11</span> <span class="o">+</span> <span class="n">S0</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">sig33</span> <span class="o">+</span> <span class="n">S0</span>
        <span class="n">D</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">S0</span> <span class="o">*</span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="n">Sx</span> <span class="o">+</span> <span class="n">Sy</span><span class="p">)</span>
        <span class="k">return</span> <span class="n">S0</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">Sx</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">Sy</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">D</span>
    
    <span class="k">def</span> <span class="nf">derivs</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="bp">self</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">moments</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">s</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">Q</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">ext_foc</span><span class="p">):</span>
        <span class="n">k0x</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">ext_foc</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">s</span><span class="p">)</span>
        <span class="n">k0y</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="o">-</span><span class="n">k0x</span>
        <span class="n">j0</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mf">0.0</span>
        <span class="n">Sigma</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="bp">self</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">vec2mat</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">moments</span><span class="p">)</span>
        <span class="n">S0</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">Sx</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">Sy</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">D</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="bp">self</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">get_shape_factors</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">Sigma</span><span class="p">)</span>
        <span class="n">kx</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">k0x</span> <span class="o">-</span> <span class="mf">0.5</span> <span class="o">*</span> <span class="n">Q</span> <span class="o">*</span> <span class="n">Sy</span> <span class="o">/</span> <span class="n">D</span>
        <span class="n">ky</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">k0y</span> <span class="o">-</span> <span class="mf">0.5</span> <span class="o">*</span> <span class="n">Q</span> <span class="o">*</span> <span class="n">Sx</span> <span class="o">/</span> <span class="n">D</span>
        <span class="n">j</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">j0</span> <span class="o">-</span> <span class="mf">0.5</span> <span class="o">*</span> <span class="n">Q</span> <span class="o">*</span> <span class="n">Sigma</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">2</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">/</span> <span class="n">D</span>
        <span class="n">M</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">array</span><span class="p">([[</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">],</span> <span class="p">[</span><span class="o">-</span><span class="n">kx</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">j</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">],</span> <span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">],</span> <span class="p">[</span><span class="n">j</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="o">-</span><span class="n">ky</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">]])</span>
        <span class="n">MSigma</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">matmul</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">M</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">Sigma</span><span class="p">)</span>
        <span class="k">return</span> <span class="bp">self</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">mat2vec</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">MSigma</span> <span class="o">+</span> <span class="n">MSigma</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">T</span><span class="p">)</span>
    
    <span class="k">def</span> <span class="nf">integrate</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="bp">self</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">Sigma</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">Q</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mf">0.0</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">foc</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="kc">None</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">distance</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mf">1.0</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">npts</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">1000</span><span class="p">):</span>

        <span class="bp">self</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">moments</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">odeint</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="bp">self</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">derivs</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="bp">self</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">mat2vec</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">Sigma</span><span class="p">),</span> <span class="bp">self</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">positions</span><span class="p">,</span>

        <span class="c1"># Return DataFrame for convenience</span>
        <span class="n">columns</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">&#39;x2&#39;</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">&#39;xxp&#39;</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">&#39;xy&#39;</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">&#39;xyp&#39;</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">&#39;xp2&#39;</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">&#39;yxp&#39;</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">&#39;xpyp&#39;</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">&#39;y2&#39;</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">&#39;yyp&#39;</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">&#39;yp2&#39;</span><span class="p">]</span>

<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="k">def</span> <span class="nf">fodo</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">s</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">quad_strength</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mf">0.556</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">cell_length</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mf">5.0</span><span class="p">):</span>
    <span class="sd">&quot;&quot;&quot;Return focusing strength at position `s` in infinite FODO lattice.&quot;&quot;&quot;</span>
    <span class="n">s</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="n">s</span> <span class="o">%</span> <span class="n">cell_length</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="o">/</span> <span class="n">cell_length</span>
    <span class="n">delta</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mf">0.125</span>
    <span class="k">if</span> <span class="n">s</span> <span class="o">&lt;</span> <span class="n">delta</span> <span class="ow">or</span> <span class="n">s</span> <span class="o">&gt;</span> <span class="mi">1</span> <span class="o">-</span> <span class="n">delta</span><span class="p">:</span>
        <span class="k">return</span> <span class="o">+</span><span class="n">quad_strength</span>
    <span class="k">elif</span> <span class="mf">0.5</span> <span class="o">-</span> <span class="n">delta</span> <span class="o">&lt;=</span> <span class="n">s</span> <span class="o">&lt;</span> <span class="mf">0.5</span> <span class="o">+</span> <span class="n">delta</span><span class="p">:</span>
        <span class="k">return</span> <span class="o">-</span><span class="n">quad_strength</span>
    <span class="k">else</span><span class="p">:</span>
        <span class="k">return</span> <span class="mf">0.0</span>
    
<span class="c1"># Create covariance matrix of KV distribution matched to lattice</span>
<span class="n">ax</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">ay</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">bx</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">by</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mf">0.0</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mf">0.0</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mf">8.017</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mf">1.544</span>
<span class="n">gx</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">1</span> <span class="o">+</span> <span class="n">ax</span><span class="o">**</span><span class="mi">2</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="o">/</span> <span class="n">bx</span>
<span class="n">gy</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">1</span> <span class="o">+</span> <span class="n">ay</span><span class="o">**</span><span class="mi">2</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="o">/</span> <span class="n">by</span>
<span class="n">ex</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">ey</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mf">25e-6</span>
<span class="n">Sigma0</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">zeros</span><span class="p">((</span><span class="mi">4</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">4</span><span class="p">))</span>
<span class="n">Sigma0</span><span class="p">[:</span><span class="mi">2</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="p">:</span><span class="mi">2</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">[[</span><span class="n">bx</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="o">-</span><span class="n">ax</span><span class="p">],</span> <span class="p">[</span><span class="o">-</span><span class="n">ax</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">gx</span><span class="p">]]</span>
<span class="n">Sigma0</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">2</span><span class="p">:,</span> <span class="mi">2</span><span class="p">:]</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">[[</span><span class="n">by</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="o">-</span><span class="n">ay</span><span class="p">],</span> <span class="p">[</span><span class="o">-</span><span class="n">ay</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">gy</span><span class="p">]]</span>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>The dashed lines show the periodic solution with space charge, and the solid line shows the same initial beam with space charge turned on. The bottom plot shows the horizontal focusing strength. A few notes on the KV distribution. First, the horizontal and vertical emittances are invariant. Second, the beam stays upright at all times.</p>
